{"text": " Have you ever tried sapodia? These fruits taste like brown sugar with a slight gritty texture similar to a pear. These trees grow great down here in South Florida and once established can start to produce fruit practically year-round, so they're a perfect addition to any food forest or garden. It'll be a little while before my tree starts to produce fruit, but fortunately my friend and Sean, over at West Davy Farms, was nice enough to share some of these with me. Definitely check out his nursery if you're local in the area. After letting it sit on the counter a few days, the fruit is now soft to the touch, which means that it's ripe and ready to be enjoyed. So all you have to do is just pull it apart with your hands, just like this, and reveal the deliciousness that's on the inside. The skin of these fruits is edible, but it's a little tough, so I prefer to just rip it into small pieces like this and eat it right out of the skin. Just like most tropical fruits, these go by a bunch of different names depending on where you're from. So let me know in the comments if you've ever tried this fruit and what you call it where you're from. And until next time, get outside and see what you can find.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 2.0, "text": " Have you ever tried sapodia?", "tokens": [50364, 3560, 291, 1562, 3031, 18985, 378, 654, 30, 50464], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1540815830230713, "compression_ratio": 1.6506666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 0.02805643156170845}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 2.0, "end": 6.36, "text": " These fruits taste like brown sugar with a slight gritty texture similar to a pear.", "tokens": [50464, 1981, 12148, 3939, 411, 6292, 5076, 365, 257, 4036, 677, 10016, 8091, 2531, 281, 257, 37320, 13, 50682], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1540815830230713, "compression_ratio": 1.6506666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 0.02805643156170845}, {"id": 2, "seek": 0, "start": 6.36, "end": 10.36, "text": " These